a_0.formal problem:
theorem
fixes x b :: real
assumes h0 : "\<forall> x. f x = x - 3"
and h1 : "\<forall> x b. q x b = b * x + 1"
and h2 : "f (q 1 b) = -3"
shows  "b = -1"
a_0.formal solution:
(* ### Problem
 Let $f(x) = x - 3$ and $q(x) = bx +1$.  If $f(q(1)) = -3$, what is $b$? The final Answer is -1
 ### Proof
 We have $q(1) = b\cdot 1 + 1 = b+1$, so $f(q(1)) = f(b+1)$.
 Applying the definition of $f$, we have $f(q(1)) = f(b+1) = (b+1) - 3 = b-2$.
 Therefore, the equation $f(q(1)) = -3$ gives us $b-2 = -3$, so $ b= \boxed{-1}$.
 *)

theorem
fixes x b :: real
assumes h0 : "\<forall> x. f x = x - 3"
and h1 : "\<forall> x b. q x b = b * x + 1"
and h2 : "f (q 1 b) = -3"
shows  "b = -1"
 proof- 
  show ?thesis sledgehammer
